<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPACE GOALS VS. EARTH GOALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With his speech proclaiming a lunar base and a trip to Mars as goals for 
America's space program, George Bush's vision of presidential leadership comes 
into focus (Part I, July 21). It is one of Potemkin politics, a grand facade of 
great intentions thrown up to hide a paralysis of will. Although Bush cannot 
offer us a clue about how to reduce the present deficit, and while even basic 
scientific research withers on the vine for lack of funding, and the health of 
America's poor deteriorates due to decimated public health budgets, he proposes 
that we embark on an extravagantly expensive space expedition. 
</P>
<P>
We deserve more from a President than mere rhetoric devoid of reason or 
responsibility. Great visions may be part of being a great leader, but without 
the courage to make hard choices, to face national problems head on and offer 
solutions, there is no leadership at all. 
</P>
<P>
CAREY P. SUBLETTE 
</P>
<P>
Riverside 
</P>
</TEXT>
