<HEADLINE>
<P>
ISRAEL PROPOSES TRADING PRISONERS WITH SHIITES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of Israel today proposed trading all his 
country's Shiite Muslim captives for all captured Israeli soldiers and foreign 
hostages held by Shiite groups in Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said they had received no immediate confirmation of a claim 
from a Shiite group that it executed a U.S. Marine hostage to retaliate for 
Israel's abduction of a Shiite cleric. 
</P>
<P>
But they reiterated Rabin's offer, made earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
"Israel repeats its call for the release of Israeli and other hostages held by 
Shiite groups in Lebanon. Israel is offering to trade prisoners, detainees and 
hostages," Rabin told reporters in Tel Aviv. 
</P>
<P>
His statement, read from a prepared text, was also broadcast on state-run 
Israel radio. Avi Pazner, spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said the 
offer was made on behalf of the government. 
</P>
<P>
"According to this proposal, all the Israeli prisoners and foreign hostages 
held by Shiite groups in Lebanon would be swapped for all the Shiite prisoners 
kept by Israel, including Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid, Jawad Kasfi and others," he 
said. "The exchange would be conducted through the International Red Cross 
according to the procedures accepted in such cases." 
</P>
<P>
Obeid is an influential Shiite Muslim cleric kidnaped by Israeli commandos 
Friday in south Lebanon, and Kasfi is another Lebanese Shiite seized by Israeli 
forces in Lebanon last December. 
</P>
<P>
Security sources estimate 50 to 60 Shiite Muslims from Lebanon are held in 
Israeli prisons. 
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia, which helps patrol Israel's 
self-declared security zone in south Lebanon, holds about 300 Shiites in a 
prison at Khiam in south Lebanon. It was not immediately clear if this group 
would be part of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Shimon Peres said earlier today that Israeli officials 
hoped that Obeid can be swapped for three Israeli soldiers missing in Lebanon 
since 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
