<P>
VIOLINIST FODOR RELEASED FROM JAIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
EDGARTOWN, Mass. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Concert violinist Eugene Fodor was released from custody today after spending 
the weekend in jail on charges he broke into a motel room and was in possession 
of drugs and a dangerous weapon. 
</P>
<P>
Fodor, 39, of New York City, had been held in lieu of $50,000 cash bail after a 
judge refused to accept his 300-year-old violin as surety. Superior Court 
Justice Joseph Mitchell today reduced bail to personal recognizance and set a 
pretrial conference Sept. 7. 
</P>
<P>
Fodor, the first American to share honors in the prestigious Tchaikovsky violin 
competition in Moscow in 1974, was arrested Friday morning after a chambermaid 
in the Vineyard Harbor Motel found him in a room that was listed as unoccupied. 
Fodor allegedly was carrying 20 grams of cocaine, a small amount of heroin, a 
dagger, a hypodermic needle and some pills when he was arrested. 
</P>
